          <h2 class="details-title">The Gateway of India: Mumbai’s Majestic Landmark</h2>
          <p>
            The Gateway of India stands proudly in Mumbai, India’s bustling financial capital, as a symbol of colonial
            history and cultural significance. Overlooking the Arabian Sea, this iconic structure attracts millions of
            tourists, history enthusiasts, and locals alike. Let’s delve into the fascinating story behind this
            architectural marvel and its significance today.
          </p>
          <h5>Historical Significance</h5>
          <p>Constructed during the British Raj, the Gateway of India was commissioned to commemorate the visit of King
            George V and Queen Mary to Bombay (now Mumbai) in December 1911. However, its foundation stone was laid in
            1913, and the final structure was completed in 1924. Designed by Scottish architect George Wittet, the
            Gateway reflects a blend of Indo-Saracenic and Islamic architectural styles, with its central arch standing
            at a height of 26 meters (85 feet).</p>
          <p>
            Interestingly, this monument was also the point where British troops departed India in 1948, marking the end
            of colonial rule. Thus, the Gateway is not only a reminder of India’s colonial past but also a symbol of the
            country’s transition to independence.
          </p>
          <h5>Architectural Grandeur</h5>
          <p>The Gateway of India’s construction incorporates yellow basalt and reinforced concrete. The intricate
            latticework, pointed arches, and exquisite carvings are prime examples of Indo-Saracenic design, which
            blends Indian, Islamic, and Gothic revival styles. Positioned facing the vast Arabian Sea, the structure
            offers an awe-inspiring view, particularly during sunrise and sunset.</p>
          <p>Flanked by lush gardens and located near prominent landmarks like the Taj Mahal Palace Hotel, the Gateway
            serves as an excellent backdrop for photography and a serene spot to enjoy the sea breeze.</p>
          <h5>Cultural and Modern-Day Relevance</h5>
          <p>The Gateway of India is more than just an architectural monument; it is a hub of activity. It serves as a
            departure point for ferries to the Elephanta Caves, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and other coastal
            destinations.</p>
          <p>For locals, the Gateway is a favorite meeting spot, and its promenade becomes lively with street food
            vendors, photographers, and souvenir sellers. It is also a popular venue for cultural events, music
            festivals, and public gatherings.</p>
          <p>During festivals, the Gateway of India is illuminated with vibrant lights, further adding to its charm. The
            monument is a true reflection of Mumbai’s cosmopolitan spirit, embracing both its historical roots and
            modern identity.</p>
          <h5>Visiting the Gateway of India</h5>
          <p>A visit to Mumbai is incomplete without experiencing the magnificence of the Gateway of India. Accessible
            by road and well-connected to other parts of the city, the monument is open to visitors throughout the year.
            While entry is free, hiring a guide can enhance the experience by providing deeper insights into its history
            and significance.</p>
          <p>Whether you’re exploring its architectural details, catching a ferry, or simply soaking in the lively
            atmosphere, the Gateway of India offers something for everyone.</p>
